  <h1>Culture, Festivals & Folk Traditions</h1>
<p>Udupi is a vibrant tapestry of coastal traditions and rituals integral to Tulu Nadu culture. Witness the energetic <em>Pili Vesha</em> (Tiger Dance) performed during Krishna Janmashtami and Navaratri, where performers painted like tigers enact dance-dramas accompanied by traditional drums :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}.</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Naga Aradhane (Serpent Worship):</strong> A centuries-old ritual held between December and April involving night-long ceremonies honouring Nagaradhane via folk art forms like Bhuta Kola :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}.</li>
  <li><strong>Kambala:</strong> The famed buffalo races—now both folk sport and tourist spectacle—take place after monsoon, showcasing speed and community pride :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}.</li>
  <li><strong>Paryaya Festival:</strong> A biennial ritual at Sri Krishna Matha where the management of the temple rotates among eight mathas, highlighted by solemn rituals and public processions :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}.</li>
</ul>

<h1>Iconic Temples & Pilgrimage Sites</h1>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Sri Krishna Matha:</strong> Founded by Madhvacharya in the 13th century, this is Udupi’s spiritual heart—extremely popular during Paryaya and Janmashtami :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}.</li>
  <li><strong>Anantheshwara Temple:</strong> A unique 8th-century Shiva-Parashurama shrine built in Kerala-style architecture, featuring a silver-seat (rajata-pitha) sanctum :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}.</li>
  <li><strong>Kollur Mookambika Temple:</strong> Around 60 km away, this shrine is an important pilgrimage site celebrated during Rathotsava with a grand chariot procession :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}.</li>
</ul>

<h1>Beaches & Islands</h1>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Malpe Beach:</strong> A lively coastal destination with a sea-walkway, Wi-Fi hotspot, and launch point to St. Mary’s Island—a basalt wonder of hexagonal rocks and scenic beauty :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}.</li>
  <li><strong>St. Mary’s Island:</strong> Accessible via Malpe, these famed islands feature unique hexagonal basalt formations and peaceful rock-strewn shores :contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}.</li>
  <li><strong>Kapu Beach & Lighthouse:</strong> Known for serene beachside ambience and a historic lighthouse overlooking the Arabian Sea :contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}.</li>
  <li><strong>Maravanthe–Trasi:</strong> A narrow strip where highway, river, backwaters, and sea meet—scheduled for eco-tourism development by the central government :contentReference[oaicite:11]{index=11}.</li>
</ul>


<h1>Education, Economy & Local Industry</h1>
<p>Udupi district is not only a spiritual hub—it’s a flourishing educational and commercial center. Manipal, within Udupi, hosts premier institutions like the Manipal Academy of Higher Education, Kasturba Medical College, and MIT :contentReference[oaicite:14]{index=14}.</p>
<p>The economy thrives on fisheries (at Malpe), agriculture (cashews, spices), handloom sarees with GI tag in progress, and local food industries. Udupi also gave birth to Syndicate Bank, Corporation Bank, Harsha Retail, and significant power plants like UPCL and Adani Power :contentReference[oaicite:15]{index=15}.</p>

<h1>Tourism & Development Initiatives</h1>
<p>The Udupi district is witnessing a surge in tourism development. The central government is evaluating a comprehensive plan to develop the unique Trasi–Maravanthe coastal stretch as a tourism cluster, highlighting the intersection of backwaters, beaches, highways, and the Western Ghats :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}.</p>
<p>Local efforts also include new pilgrim-center developments in Karkala—such as Bahubali at Anekere and Varanga Jain Basadi—under the Swadesh Darshan scheme with ₹116 crore funding :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}. Udupi's peaceful reputation even prompted the MLA to urge removal from Special Action Force oversight to preserve its appeal to educators, investors, students, and tourists :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}.</p>

<h1>Empowering Local Women & Entrepreneurs</h1>
<p>Udupi has launched “Akka Sanjeevini Angadi”, women-led outlets that sell products made by Sanjeevini self-help groups—empowering local female artisans and creating rural income streams :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}.</p>

<h1>Beaches, Marine Life & Coastal Initiatives</h1>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Malpe Beach & Sea Walkway:</strong> With free Wi‑Fi and a scenic sea‑walkway, Malpe offers easy access to St. Mary’s Island and coral reefs on the Gaveshani Bank :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}.</li>
  <li><strong>Trasi–Maravanthe Stretch:</strong> Identified for eco-tourism and coastal experience development due to its rare river-backwater-sea alignment :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}.</li>
  <li><strong>Pilgrimage Centres of Karkala:</strong> Linked with eco-cultural tourism, plans are in motion for thematic circuits connecting religious and natural heritage :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}.</li>
</ul>


